{"continue":{"rvcontinue":"20141119222208|634604835","continue":"||"},"warnings":{"main":{"*":"Subscribe to the mediawiki-api-announce mailing list at <https://lists.wikimedia.org/mailman/listinfo/mediawiki-api-announce> for notice of API deprecations and breaking changes. Use [[Special:ApiFeatureUsage]] to see usage of deprecated features by your application."},"revisions":{"*":"Because \"rvslots\" was not specified, a legacy format has been used for the output. This format is deprecated, and in the future the new format will always be used."}},"query":{"normalized":[{"from":"Allyson_Schwartz","to":"Allyson Schwartz"}],"pages":{"1147061":{"pageid":1147061,"ns":0,"title":"Allyson Schwartz","revisions":[{"timestamp":"2014-11-19T22:23:17Z","contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"{{Infobox Officeholder\n|name          = Allyson Schwartz\n|image         = Allyson Schwartz official photo.jpg\n|state         = [[Pennsylvania]]\n|district      = {{ushr|Pennsylvania|13|13th}}\n|term_start    = January 3, 2005\n|term_end      = <!--January 3, 2015-->\n|predecessor   = [[Joe Hoeffel]]\n|successor     = [[Brendan Boyle]] <small>(elect)</small>\n|state_senate1 = Pennsylvania\n|district1     = [[Pennsylvania Senate, District 4|4th]]\n|term_start1   = January 1, 1991\n|term_end1     = January 4, 2005<ref>{{cite web |title = SESSION OF 2005 189TH OF THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY No. 1|work = Legislative Journal| publisher = Pennsylvania Senate|date = 2005-01-04|url = http://www.legis.state.pa.us/WU01/LI/SJ/2005/0/Sj20050104.pdf}}</ref>\n|predecessor1  = [[Joe Rocks]]\n|successor1    = [[LeAnna Washington]]\n|birthname     = Allyson Young\n|birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1948|10|3}}\n|birth_place   = [[Queens|New York City]], [[New York]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n|death_date    = \n|death_place   = \n|party         = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|spouse        = David Schwartz\n|alma_mater    = [[Simmons College]]<br>[[Bryn Mawr College]]\n|religion      = [[Judaism]]\n|website       = [http://schwartz.house.gov/index.shtml Government website]<br>[http://www.allysonschwartz.com Campaign website]\n}}\n'''Allyson Young Schwartz''' (born October 3, 1948) is the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for {{ushr|PA|13}}, serving since 2005. She is a member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]]. The district includes parts of [[Montgomery County, Pennsylvania|Montgomery County]] and [[Northeast Philadelphia]]. She is also National Chair for Recruitment and Candidate Services for the [[Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee]]. In the [[Pennsylvania gubernatorial election, 2014|2014 election]], Schwartz was a candidate for the Democratic nomination for [[List of Governors of Pennsylvania|Governor of Pennsylvania]], but was defeated in the primary.\n\n==Early life, education, and health care career==\nSchwartz was born Allyson Young in [[Queens]], [[New York]], to Everett and Renee (n\u00e9e Perl) Young. Her mother left [[Vienna]] in 1938 after [[Germany]] annexed [[Austria]], and came to the [[United States]], where she settled at a [[Jew]]ish [[Foster care|foster home]] in [[Philadelphia]]. Her father was a [[Dentistry|dentist]] in [[Flushing, Queens]], and a veteran of the [[Korean War]]. She has a brother, Neal, and two sisters, Nancy and Dale.<ref name=campaignbio>{{cite web|title=About Allyson|url=http://www.allysonschwartz.com/about|work=AllysonSchwartz.com|accessdate=6 March 2013}}</ref> Schwartz graduated from the [[Calhoun School]], on the [[Upper West Side]] of [[New York City]], in 1966 and then enrolled at [[Simmons College (Massachusetts)|Simmons College]] in [[Boston]], [[Massachusetts]]. She earned a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree in Sociology from Simmons in 1970, as well as a [[Master of Social Work]] degree from [[Bryn Mawr College]] in 1972.\n\nShe worked as assistant director of the Philadelphia Health Services Department from 1972 to 1975, and executive director of the Elizabeth Blackwell Center, a [[Planned Parenthood]] clinic in Philadelphia, from 1975 to 1988.\n\n==Pennsylvania Senate==\n\n===Elections===\nIn 1990, Schwartz ran for Pennsylvania's 4th senate seat, based in Northwest and [[Northeast Philadelphia]]. She won the Democratic primary with 50% of the vote, defeating Jeff Blum (28%) and Robert Blasi (22%).<ref>http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=754989</ref> In the general election, Schwartz defeated incumbent [[United States Republican Party|Republican]] State Senator [[Joe Rocks]] 58%-42%.<ref>http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=754966</ref>\n\nAfter redistricting, the district extended into [[Montgomery County, Pennsylvania|Montgomery County]]. In 1994, she won re-election to a second term by defeating Republican Tom Scott 82%-18%.<ref>http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=228855</ref> In 1998, she won re-election to a third term unopposed.<ref>http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=187876</ref> In [[Pennsylvania Senate elections, 2002|2002]], she won re-election to a fourth term defeating Republican Ron Holt, the Montgomery County Register of Wills, 82%-18%.<ref>http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=38066</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nDuring her first term, Schwartz led Pennsylvania\u2019s legislative efforts to provide health care coverage to the children of middle-class families, leading to the creation of the Children\u2019s Health Insurance Program (CHIP) in 1992. CHIP served as the model for the federal plan that now provides health insurance to millions of children.<ref>{{cite web|title=Third Way Co-Chair Allyson Schwartz|url=http://www.thirdway.org/co_chairs/22|work=Third Way|accessdate=6 March 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2002 [[PoliticsPA]] feature story designating politicians with yearbook superlatives, she was named the \"Best Dressed,\" to which she responded \"I appreciate the honor...it must be the scarves.\"<ref name=yearbook>{{cite web| title =Keystone State Yearbook Committee|  work = [[PoliticsPA]]| publisher =The Publius Group | year = 2001| url = http://www.politicspa.com/yearbookcommittee.htm|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20020803170058/www.politicspa.com/yearbookcommittee.htm|archivedate=2002-08-31}}</ref>\n\nShe strongly supported an assault weapons ban.\n\n===Committee assignments===\n*Education (Ranking Member)<ref>{{cite news|title= Lawmakers Ok Charter Schools| url=http://articles.philly.com/1997-06-12/news/25525538_1_charter-schools-charter-bill-school-reforms |work = Philadelphia Daily News| date=12 June 1997}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=PG&p_theme=pg&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EADFB94D2A19617&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM | work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette | date=3 June 1997}}</ref>\n*Insurance<ref>{{cite news| url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=PI&s_site=philly&p_multi=PI&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB5CDD275C7B692&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM | date=26 February 1999}}</ref>\n\n==2000 U.S. Senate election==\n{{See also|United States Senate election in Pennsylvania, 2000}}\nIn [[United States Senate election in Pennsylvania, 2000|2000]], she decided to challenge [[United States Republican Party|Republican]] U.S. Senator [[Rick Santorum]]. [[Pittsburgh]]-area U.S. Congressman [[Ron Klink]] won the crowded, six-candidate Democratic primary with a plurality of 41% of the vote. Schwartz ranked second with 27% of the vote, dominating the southeastern part of the state, most notably Philadelphia (60%) and Montgomery (62%) counties. She also won two counties outside of the region: Centre (33%) and Union (38%). However, this was not enough to overcome Klink's dominance in the western part of the state.<ref>http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=127072</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===Elections===\n;2004\nIn 2003, Democratic U.S. Congressman [[Joe Hoeffel]], of [[Pennsylvania's 13th congressional district]], decided not to run for a fourth term, in order to challenge Republican U.S. Senator [[Arlen Specter]]. Schwartz had originally planned to run for [[Auditor General of Pennsylvania|Auditor General]], but changed her plans after Hoeffel's announcement. In early 2004, she moved from Philadelphia to [[Jenkintown, Pennsylvania|Jenkintown]] in Montgomery County, where she still lives today. She won the Democratic primary, narrowly defeating former [[Philadelphia]] deputy mayor and [[National Constitution Center]] director [[Joe Torsella]] 52%-48%. She won 62% of Montgomery while Torsella won 57% of Philadelphia.<ref>http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=5104</ref> While most former state legislators raise comparatively more money through [[Political action committee|PACs]] than individual donations, she raised $4,597,032<ref>[http://www.opensecrets.org/states/election.asp?State=PA&year=2004 Pennsylvania Congressional Races in 2008<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> from individual donations and comparatively little ($558,376) in PAC donations. The 13th had long been reckoned as a classic moderate southeastern Republican district, but had become increasingly Democratic in recent years. A Republican presidential candidate hasn't carried it since 1988, and it has been in Democratic hands for all but four years since 1993. In the general election, she defeated Republican Melissa Brown 56%-41%, winning both counties.<ref>http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=4327</ref>\n\n;2006\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Pennsylvania, 2006#13th Congressional district}}\nSchwartz won re-election to a second term, defeating [[Raj Bhakta]], a contestant on the [[The Apprentice (US Season 2)|''The Apprentice 2'']], 66%-34%.<ref>http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=207670</ref>\n\n;2008\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Pennsylvania, 2008#District 13}}\nSchwartz won re-election to a third term, defeating Republican attorney [[Marina Kats]], 63%-35%.<ref>http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=324563</ref>\n\n;2010\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Pennsylvania, 2010#District 13}}\nSchwartz won re-election to a fourth term, defeating businessman [[Dee Adcock]] 56%-44%. Her 12-point margin was the smallest in her congressional career.<ref>http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=493135</ref>\n\n;2012\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Pennsylvania, 2012#District 13}}\nAfter redistricting, Schwartz's district was given a heavier Democratic tilt, with 52% of the district based in [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania|Philadelphia county]]. She won re-election to a fifth term, defeating Republican Joe Rooney 69%-31%.<ref>http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=751811</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Di Domizio|first=Tony|title=Schwartz Wins Fifth Term in 13th Congressional District|url=http://uppermoreland.patch.com/articles/schwartz-ahead-in-13th-congressional-race-ongoing|accessdate=6 March 2013|newspaper=Upmoorland Patch|date=6 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nSchwartz is a member of the [[New Democrat Coalition]] and was the chair of the New Democrat Coalition Taskforce on Health. In this position, she had actively pushed for the greater use of interoperable and secure [[electronic prescribing]] systems throughout the country in an attempt to decrease medical errors as well as costs and liability to providers, health systems and patients. In January 2014, Schwartz resigned from the taskforce chairmanship in the New Democratic Coalition.\n\nSchwartz was the first Democratic member of the House of Representatives to call for Rep. [[Anthony Weiner]] to resign following his [[Anthony Weiner photo scandal|photo scandal]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Jackson|first=Jill|title=First House Democrat calls for Weiner to step down|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-503544_162-20070156-503544.html|work=CBS News|publisher=CBS Interactive Inc.|accessdate=8 June 2011|deadurl=yes}} {{Dead link|date=April 2014|bot=RjwilmsiBot}}</ref>\n\nRepresentative Schwartz voted against the Amash amendment to limit NSA surveillance activities.\n\n;Abortion\nSchwartz is pro-choice, and in 2011 received a 100% rating from [[NARAL]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Rep. Allyson Schwartz|url=http://www.prochoiceamerica.org/elections/2012/voter-guide/schwartz-allyson.html|work=NARAL Pro-Choice America|accessdate=6 March 2013}}</ref> She voted twice against Republican-led efforts to defund Planned Parenthood, and supported legislation requiring hospitals to provide emergency abortion care to women who could die without it.\n\n;Health care\nSchwartz is known as one of the leading health care experts in government.<ref name=aca />  She authored several key provisions of the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]], including increasing access to primary care, banning pre-existing conditions exclusions and allowing young adults to remain on their parent\u2019s health coverage.<ref name=campaignbio /><ref name=aca>{{cite news|last=Jick|first=Jeremy|title=Rep. Allyson Schwartz leads Affordable Care Act discussion|url=http://www.thedp.com/article/2012/11/rep-allyson-schwartz-leads-affordable-care-act-discussion|accessdate=6 March 2013|newspaper=The Daily Pennsylvanian|date=12 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n;Veterans\nThe first piece of legislation Schwartz introduced after being elected to Congress focused on providing tax credits to businesses that hire unemployed veterans. The bill was signed into law in 2007. In 2011, Schwartz introduced the Hiring Our Veterans Act, which was signed into law by President Obama in November of that year.<ref>{{cite web|title=Biography of Allyson Y. Schwartz|url=http://schwartz.house.gov/about-me/biography|work=House.gov|accessdate=6 March 2013}}</ref>  The Hiring Our Veterans Act increased the tax credit for employers that hire veterans with a service connected disability who have been unemployed for six months or more, veterans who have been unemployed for at least four weeks, and veterans, not necessarily with disability, who have been unemployed for at least six months.\n\nIn 2012, Schwartz introduced the Servicemembers' Access to Justice Act to improve the enforcement of Uniformed Services Employment and Reemployment Rights Act of 1994.<ref>{{cite web|title=H.R.6015 - Servicemembers Access to Justice Act of 2012|url=http://www.opencongress.org/bill/112-h6015/show|work=OpenCongress|accessdate=6 March 2013}}</ref>  Schwartz was backed by Senator Bob Casey, who introduced this legislation in the Senate on May 23, 2012 (Schwartz, 2012).\n\n===Committee assignments===\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Ways and Means|Committee on Ways and Means]]'''\n\nPrior to 2013 she was also a member of the [[United States House Committee on Foreign Affairs|Committee on Foreign Affairs]], and prior to 2014 she was the Vice-Ranking Member of the [[United States House Committee on the Budget|Committee on the Budget]].\n\n==2014 gubernatorial election==\n{{Main|Pennsylvania gubernatorial election, 2014}}\nSchwartz announced her intention to give up her House seat to challenge incumbent Republican Pennsylvania Governor [[Tom Corbett]], who is up for re-election in 2014.<ref name=pdnews>{{cite web|url=http://www.philly.com/philly/news/politics/state/20130225_John_Baer__Allyson_Schwartz_admits_her_interest_in_Pa__governor_s_race.html|work=[[Philadelphia Daily News]]|title=John Baer: Allyson Schwartz admits her interest in Pa. governor's race |last=Baer|first=John|date=February 25, 2013|accessdate=February 25, 2013}}</ref> On April 8, 2013, Schwartz officially launched her campaign.<ref>{{cite news|last=Camia|first=Catalina|title=Dem Rep. Schwartz jumps into Pa. governor's race|url=http://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2013/04/08/allyson-schwartz-pennsylvania-governor-corbett/2063863/|work=USA Today|date=April 9, 2013}}</ref> In February 2013, Schwartz stated that she would not run for re-election for the United States House of Representatives.<ref>{{cite web|last=Baer|first=John|title=Allyson Schwartz admits her interest in Pa. governor's race|url=http://articles.philly.com/2013-02-26/news/37291228_1_allyson-schwartz-tom-corbett-woman-governor|work=Philadelphia Daily News|date=February 26, 2013}}</ref> Ultimately, she was defeated by [[Tom Wolf (politician)|Tom Wolf]] in the Democratic primary.<ref name=primaryloss>{{cite news|last=Foster|first=Brittany|title=PA-Gov: Wolf Wins Democratic Nomination|url=http://www.politicspa.com/pa-gov-wolf-wins-democratic-nomination/58081/|accessdate=21 May 2014|newspaper=PoliticsPA|date=20 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nSchwartz is married to Dr. David Schwartz, a cardiologist, and they live in [[Jenkintown, Pennsylvania|Jenkintown]], [[Pennsylvania]]. They have two adult sons, Daniel and Jordan.<ref name=campaignbio />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n*Berkman, Michael, and James Eisenstein. \u201cState Legislators as Candidates: The Effects of Prior Experience on Legislative Behavior and Fundraising,\u201d Political Science Quarterly, 52, no. 3 (1999): 481\u2013498.\n\n== External links ==\n{{commonscat-inline}}\n*[http://www.house.gov/schwartz Congresswoman Allyson Y. Schwartz] official U.S. House site\n*[http://www.allysonschwartz.com Allyson Schwartz for Governor] \n*{{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Pennsylvania/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Allyson_Schwartz_%5BD-13%5D}}\n*{{CongLinks | congbio = s001162 | ballot = Allyson_Schwartz | nndb = 306/000087045 | votesmart = 5239 | govtrack = 400647 | opencong = 400647 | rollcall = 7143 | politifact = | legistorm = 465/Rep_Allyson_Young_Schwartz.html | fec